---

ServiceImpl

Replace your getFedexSubscription() with this.

@Override
public FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse getFedexSubscription(
        String customerId,
        String accountNumber) {

    log.info(new LogBuilder()
            .withMessage("Fetching FedEx subscription details")
            .withField("customerId", customerId)
            .withField("accountNumber", accountNumber)
            .toString());

    List<FedexSubscriptionEntity> subscriptions =
            fedexSubscriptionRepository.findByCustomerId(customerId);

    if (subscriptions.isEmpty()) {

        log.info(new LogBuilder()
                .withMessage("Customer not found")
                .withField("customerId", customerId)
                .toString());

        return null;
    }

    for (FedexSubscriptionEntity subscription : subscriptions) {

        long accountCount =
                fedexSubscriptionRepository.countAccountsBySubscriptionId(
                        subscription.getSubscriptionId());

        /*
         * More than 500 accounts
         */
        if (accountCount > 500) {

            return FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse.builder()
                    .registrationId(subscription.getRegistrationId())
                    .subscriptionId(null)
                    .accountNumber(accountNumber)
                    .build();
        }

        /*
         * Account exists
         */
        Optional<String> account =
                fedexSubscriptionRepository.findAccountNumber(
                        subscription.getSubscriptionId(),
                        accountNumber);

        if (account.isPresent()) {

            return FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse.builder()
                    .registrationId(subscription.getRegistrationId())
                    .subscriptionId(subscription.getSubscriptionId())
                    .accountNumber(account.get())
                    .build();
        }

        /*
         * Customer exists but account doesn't
         */
        return FedexSubscriptionFetchResponse.builder()
                .registrationId(subscription.getRegistrationId())
                .subscriptionId(subscription.getSubscriptionId())
                .accountNumber(null)
                .build();
    }

    return null;
}


---

This covers every scenario

Scenario	registrationId	subscriptionId	accountNumber

Customer not found	null	null	null
Customer exists, account missing	✅	✅	null
Customer + account exists	✅	✅	✅
Subscription >500 accounts	✅	null	request account



---

Why I recommend this

Your tech lead is likely to prefer this because:

Repository methods each have a single responsibility.

Business rules (>500, account exists, etc.) stay in the service, not in JPQL.

Easy to unit test.

Easy to modify later if the threshold changes from 500 to another value.


This follows a cleaner service/repository separation than trying to encode all the logic in one complex query.